      "text": "**Refining Import Logic**\n\nI'm now focusing on the Excel import process, aiming to use column K (\"reunion_asignada\") as the central identifier for grouping meetings. My aim is to organize churches and zones effectively, based on the values in this crucial column, to simplify the generation of the \"Calendario Territorial\" view. I'm exploring how to make this grouping both accurate and efficient.\n\n\n**Organizing By Meeting**\n\nI'm now integrating the \"reunion_asignada\" column (likely accessible as `row.reunion_asignada` after parsing the Excel) into the import logic. My focus is on using this data to properly group churches for the \"Calendario Territorial\" view. I'm aiming to streamline this aspect to ensure accurate and efficient organization based on meeting titles. This column will be central to sorting churches into their respective meetings.\n\n\n**Adapting Import Logic**\n\nI'm now revising the approach to rely on the \"reunion_asignada\" string from Excel as the meeting name for grouping. This means updating `ChurchManagement.tsx` to set `meetingId` to `row.reunion_asignada` when importing. This name will serve as the unique meeting key. I need to make sure the program handles this string input effectively for consistent organization.\n\n\n**Updating Meeting Integration**\n\nI'm now thinking about how to handle the meeting data. I need to make sure the program properly uses the \"reunion_asignada\" data for meeting organization. When importing, I should probably identify and update the `meetings` state to include any new meetings found in the Excel data, and add the unique ones to our `meetings` list. My focus is on ensuring this mapping and organization are accurate and consistent with the user's intent to view the territorial calendar by meeting title, instead of filtering only by zone. This means I'll need to modify both import logic and `Calendario Territorial` logic.\n\n\n**Confirming Column Importance**\n\nI've confirmed that \"reunion\\_asignada\" is indeed the crucial key for meeting grouping. I plan to modify `ChurchManagement.tsx` to directly utilize this column for parsing. Also, I'll update `MeetingManagement.tsx` to enable church viewing based on their meeting names, and ensure churches with matching `meetingId` display correctly. Furthermore, I need to update the bulk import handler to handle meetings synthesized from the string values. I'll focus on making the `meetingId` a string to simplify the grouping process, since \"reunion_asignada\" is the source of truth.\n\n\n**Implementing Meeting Generation**\n\nI'm now focusing on implementing the dynamic meeting generation. I'm modifying `ChurchManagement.tsx` to directly pull the `reunion_asignada` string for `meetingId`. Next, I will modify `MeetingManagement.tsx` to handle these dynamic meeting names. Lastly, I will revise `App.tsx` to create a list of \"Virtual Meetings\" based on the unique `reunion_asignada` values in the church data, so that they show up on the territorial calendar.\n\n\n**Refining Meeting Display**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on dynamically displaying meetings in `MeetingManagement.tsx`. My current plan is to modify the \"Grid de Reuniones\" to show meetings based on the unique strings in the `reunion_asignada` data from the Excel import. I want the user to see a list of unique \"Meetings\" found within the dataset. I will need to handle this both for new and existing meetings.\n\n\n**Adapting Data Mapping**\n\nI'm now integrating the string value of \"reunion_asignada\" as the `meetingId` from the Excel data into `ChurchManagement.tsx`. My goal is to ensure this string is correctly stored and utilized within the ChurchLeader objects. I need to update the `getMeetingName` function so that it displays the string meeting name directly when a matching meeting is not found in the `meetings` state. Additionally, I plan to derive \"Reuniones\" dynamically from the `churches` data within `MeetingManagement.tsx`.\n\n\n\n"